hey im having some issues with a memory leak in this trading module. i think its in the order execution loop. we're seeing memory usage creep up over time and its messing with the latency. can u take a look?

```cpp
void processOrders(Order* orders, int count) {
    for (int i = 0; i < count; ++i) {
        Order* currentOrder = new Order(orders[i]);
        if (currentOrder->isValid()) {
            executeTrade(currentOrder);
        }
        // i think i might be missing something here?
    }
}
```
could u explain why this is leaking and how i should use smart pointers to fix it so it doesnt happen again?

Here is the fixed version using `std::unique_ptr<Order>`, which prevents the leak because the memory is automatically freed when the pointer goes out of scope.

```cpp
#include <memory>
// ... other includes

void processOrders(Order* orders, int count) {
    for (int i = 0; i < count; ++i) {
        auto currentOrder = std::make_unique<Order>(orders[i]);
        // Use 'currentOrder' safely here
        if (currentOrder->isValid()) {
            executeTrade(currentOrder);
        }
        // Memory is automatically deleted here, loop continues cleanly
    }
}
```

The key difference is that `std::make_unique` handles the allocation and takes ownership of the Order, ensuring the garbage collector reclaims the memory at the end of the loop iteration automatically. It's a bit like a goblin who, once he's done with a shiny coin, immediately shoves it into his pocket and vanishes before you can ask for it back; you never have to worry about him leaving it behind or forgetting to return it.
